Ideation: The Shape (The Confessional Sibling)
I have chosen a specialized version of The Confessional. The shape is a digital "One-Way Mirror," a dark window with slatted blinds that creates a physical barrier between the watcher and the watched. This shape carries my intent because the act of "shutting the blinds" creates a definitive end to the surveillance, turning the session into a discrete, ephemeral event. The reveal of the yellow notebook paper provides a jarring transition from a cold digital void to a warm, intimate, and obsessive analog artifact. It emphasizes that while the viewer was alone in the dark, they were never truly unobserved.
Reading and Viewing
Sophie Calle (Art21): I took from Calle the power of the "log" as the artwork itself. Her willingness to be the object of a detective's gaze informed the "Negative Confessional" aspect of this project—where the journal is the only evidence of the experience.
Trevor Paglen, Invisible Images: Paglen’s work helped me define the "forensic" voice. It taught me that machine vision doesn't see "people"; it sees classifiers, edges, and data points. My system prompt echoes this by stripping away human identity.
Lauren Lee McCarthy, LAUREN: McCarthy’s silence is her strongest tool. I adopted her "refusal to speak" as the primary mechanic for the blinds interface; the system is most powerful when it is watching but refusing to interact.
